    readTime: '5 min',
    sections: [],
    richSections: [
      { type: 'paragraph', content: 'If you are a Medicare beneficiary and suffer a work-related injury or illness, both Medicare and workers\u2019 compensation (WC) may be involved in paying for your care. The rules governing which payer goes first and how settlements are handled are set by the Medicare Secondary Payer (MSP) Act.' },
      { type: 'heading', level: 2, text: 'Who Pays First: Medicare or Workers\u2019 Comp?', id: 'who-pays-first' },
      { type: 'paragraph', content: 'Workers\u2019 compensation is the primary payer for medical expenses related to a work injury. Medicare is secondary, meaning it only pays after workers\u2019 comp has paid its share. If workers\u2019 comp denies a claim or delays payment, Medicare may make a conditional payment to cover your care, but it will seek reimbursement once the WC claim is resolved.' },
      { type: 'table', title: 'Medicare and Workers\u2019 Comp: Payer Order', headers: ['Situation', 'Primary Payer', 'Secondary Payer'], rows: [
        ['Active workers\u2019 comp claim for work-related injury', 'Workers\u2019 compensation', 'Medicare (conditional)'],
        ['Workers\u2019 comp denies or delays payment', 'Medicare (conditional payment)', 'Workers\u2019 comp (must reimburse Medicare)'],
        ['Non-work-related medical expenses', 'Medicare', 'Other supplemental coverage'],
      ]},
      { type: 'heading', level: 2, text: 'Conditional Payments and Reimbursement', id: 'conditional-payments' },
      { type: 'paragraph', content: 'If Medicare pays for treatment related to your work injury while your WC claim is pending, those are called conditional payments. Medicare has the right to recover these payments from any WC settlement or award you receive. You or your attorney must notify the Benefits Coordination and Recovery Center (BCRC) when a WC claim is filed and when a settlement is reached.' },
      { type: 'callout', calloutType: 'warning', calloutTitle: 'Notify Medicare Before Settling', calloutText: 'Before finalizing a workers\u2019 compensation settlement, you must address any Medicare conditional payments and, if applicable, set up a Medicare Set-Aside arrangement. Failing to do so can result in Medicare refusing to pay for future related care until the set-aside funds are exhausted.' },
      { type: 'heading', level: 2, text: 'What Is a Medicare Set-Aside (MSA)?', id: 'msa' },
      { type: 'paragraph', content: 'A Medicare Set-Aside (MSA) is a portion of a workers\u2019 compensation settlement that is allocated to pay for future medical expenses related to the work injury that Medicare would otherwise cover. The Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) reviews proposed MSA amounts for settlements that meet certain thresholds. Once the MSA funds are exhausted, Medicare will begin paying for covered future care.' },
      { type: 'heading', level: 2, text: 'Periodic Payments vs. Lump-Sum Settlements', id: 'periodic-vs-lump-sum' },
      { type: 'paragraph', content: 'Workers\u2019 comp benefits can be paid as ongoing periodic payments or as a lump-sum settlement. With periodic payments, Medicare typically pays for medical expenses not covered by WC. With a lump-sum settlement, Medicare may not pay for related medical expenses until the settlement amount allocated for medical care has been spent down, even if the settlement did not specifically designate funds for medical costs.' },
      { type: 'faq', faqs: [
        { question: 'Does Medicare cover injuries that workers\u2019 comp does not?', answer: 'Medicare may cover medical expenses for a work-related injury if workers\u2019 comp denies the claim or does not cover a specific treatment. However, Medicare will make a conditional payment and seek reimbursement if WC later pays.' },
        { question: 'What happens if I do not reimburse Medicare after a WC settlement?', answer: 'Medicare has the right to recover conditional payments from your settlement. If you do not reimburse Medicare, it can pursue collection through the Department of Justice and may refuse to pay for future related care.' },
        { question: 'Do I need an attorney for a workers\u2019 comp settlement involving Medicare?', answer: 'It is strongly recommended. An attorney experienced in Medicare Secondary Payer rules can help ensure conditional payments are properly identified and that any MSA arrangement is structured correctly to protect your future Medicare benefits.' },
      ]},
    ],
